93
00:08:01,120 --> 00:08:08,400
Standard audio processors, the tech that runs our podcasts, our music apps, everything they sample will sound uniformly.

94
00:08:09,020 --> 00:08:17,100
They take a snapshot of the sound wave thousands of times a second, like 44,100 times a second for CD quality.

95
00:08:17,280 --> 00:08:18,960
That is the industry standard, yes.

96
00:08:19,040 --> 00:08:22,480
But this system uses something called event-based sampling.

97
00:08:22,480 --> 00:08:27,220
It actively ignores most of the waves and only tracks the peaks.

98
00:08:28,000 --> 00:08:30,040
This is a critical pivot in the methodology.

99
00:08:31,360 --> 00:08:36,920
Uniform sampling looks at a waveform mechanically, driven by an external clock.

100
00:08:37,740 --> 00:08:43,040
It takes a measurement every few microseconds, regardless of what the sound wave is actually doing.

101
00:08:43,460 --> 00:08:44,860
Just a blind metronome.

102
00:08:45,040 --> 00:08:45,520
Exactly.

103
00:08:45,520 --> 00:08:54,640
But the marine processor, which is the actual rust-based software engine implementing this framework, takes a biological approach.

104
00:08:55,180 --> 00:08:56,440
It waits for an event.

105
00:08:57,140 --> 00:09:00,560
It specifically looks for local maxima of the signal.

106
00:09:00,960 --> 00:09:03,900
It only records data when the sound wave hits a peak.

107
00:09:04,140 --> 00:09:10,420
But wait, I have to push back on this, because that sounds like a terrible idea if the goal is preserving human emotion.

