00:09:18,180 --> 00:09:24,680
specifically because the space between the peaks contains the warmth, the richness, the nuance of the sound.

111
00:09:25,400 --> 00:09:31,480
If we're only tracking the peaks, aren't we throwing away, like, 99% of the actual sound wave?

112
00:09:32,000 --> 00:09:38,020
Doesn't skipping all that non-peak data mean we're losing the exact nuance we're trying to save?

113
00:09:38,020 --> 00:09:42,740
It completely defies our intuition about high-fidelity audio, I know.

114
00:09:43,760 --> 00:09:47,040
But we have to separate audio reproduction from prosodic measurement.

115
00:09:47,440 --> 00:09:47,680
Okay.

116
00:09:48,100 --> 00:09:55,000
If you want to play the sound back through a speaker and have it sound like a human in the room, yes, you absolutely need the whole wave.

